obo:GO_0003674  a  owl:Class .

gomodel:SYNGO_4072  a     owl:Ontology ;
        rdfs:comment      "Rationale: This paper introduces a new technique to measure DCV exocytosis kinetics using high-resolution membrane capacitance (Cm) combined with Ca2+ uncaging stimuli.\n\nFigure 2A: Average Cm responses (bottom) induced by similar [Ca2+]i elevations (top) in wild-type (black trace), unc-31 mutant (red trace), unc-64 mutant (blue trace), and unc-18 mutant (grey trace) cells are compared. The inset compares the amplitude of burst exocytosis between wild-type, unc-31, unc-64, unc-18, and tag-81 mutant cells. The exocytotic burst is quantified as the amplitude of the exponential fit to the Cm trace.\nDrastic reduction (~85%) in the amplitude of burst exocytosis of the Unc18 mutant indicates its role in DCV exocytosis.\n\nFigure 7A: Density of near-membrane DCVs per unit area was slightly smaller in unc-18(e81) neurons.\nFigure 7B: The average docking rate per unit area per minute was considerably reduced (by ~58%) in unc-18(e81) mutant cells.\nFigure 7C: Docking events in the absence of UNC-18 were in general much shorter than those from wild-type cells.\n\nTogether, the data suggest that Unc18 plays a key role in presynaptic DCV exocytosis.. Experimental description: IDA-1::gfp KM246 (Cai et al., 2004) strain was further crossed with unc-18(e81), unc-31(e928), unc-64(e246), unc-13(e51) (Brenner, 1974), tag-81(ok614) (Richmond et al., 1999) mutants for production of transgenic lines. (Supplementary information)" ;
        lego:modelstate   "production" ;
        dc:contributor    "https://orcid.org/0000-0003-2916-7616" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2286-1587" , "https://orcid.org/0000-0002-2514-0216" ;
        dc:date           "2020-12-08" ;
        dc:title          "SYNGO_BP_4072" ;
        pav:providedBy    "https://syngo.vu.nl" ;
        biolink:in_taxon  "http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/NCBITaxon_6239" .

